\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Operational Procedures
\series default
:
 Recurring procedures,
 system workflows,
 and escalation paths not covered by the categories above.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Reference Documentation
\series default
:
 Static informational artifacts that document the state of the environment and support operational decision-making,
 including network schemas,
 addressing plans,
 VLAN tables,
 topology diagrams,
 and system architecture overviews.
 Reference Documentation entries do not prescribe action steps and are not subject to the structured procedure format requirement in Section 6.3.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Ownership and review obligations for each category shall follow the roles defined in Section 3.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.3 Structured Procedure Format
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
All KB procedures shall document tasks as discrete,
 sequentially numbered steps.
 KB procedures shall address known error conditions and their corresponding recovery actions as conditional branches within the step sequence.
 KB procedures shall specify the expected end state upon successful completion.
 The Assistant IT Director shall establish and maintain the formatting conventions and templates implementing these requirements as an operational standard.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.4 Standard Change Authorization Function
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
A KB procedure qualifies a change type as Standard only when the procedure carries explicit IT Director approval.
 If no qualifying KB procedure exists for a given change type,
 the change type shall default to Significant classification under 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:3.09"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
.
 The IT Director shall approve retirement or material modification of any Standard change procedure through the same approval path as creation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.5 Known Error Entry Lifecycle
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Known Error entries are a distinct KB record type.
 The Known Error declaration and closure triggers,
 including publication and inactivation timeframes,
 are governed by 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
